 <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=397889"> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.boomspeed.com/balthag/BaltSig.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gravely>Gravely</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 130<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/16/03 5:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm45.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.visi.com/~mlm/eq/gravely_face_60x60.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: nd-3</span><hr size=1> In my opinion, the best caster AA period is SCM3 (spell casting mastery).  Don't read the in-game description, it was obviously not written by anyone who had any contact with the actual programmers.<br>
<br>
Here's what Specialization does, first.<br>
<br>
With a specialization skill in a given area, you take skill / 20, and that's the percent mana you save every time you cast a spell of that school.  For example, if you have Specialize: Alteration at 200, you save 10% of the mana cost off each Alteration spell you cast.  For example, for a cleric casting Complete Healing (400 mana), it really costs 360 mana.  Extensive testing by the same type of people who fight a mob for 10 hours to get a good parse and figure out how much AC is affecting a fight (math/statistics geeks like me) has shown that Specializations do nothing as far as channeling, fizzling, etc. go.  There is no &quot;specialization check&quot; to see if you save mana.  That's not how the code is working.  Extensive testing has shown it does one thing: saves a specific percent of mana per spell cast every time you cast it.<br>
<br>
Now, what Spell Casting Mastery does is increases the effect of Specialization.  Think of it as raising all your Spec skills by 200-250 for SCM3 (the exact number isn't known, but testing puts it in that range and most people seem to think it's in the higher end).  So, you get roughly 200-250 divided by 20 = 10% to 12.5% more mana savings for <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>every</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> spell you cast.  Complete Heal for clerics now costs somewhere between 310 and 320 mana per cast instead of the base 400.  Now, if you're having trouble believing this, let's take something I'm sure every caster has experienced, and see how this mana savings caused by Specialization and Spell Casting Mastery explain it.  You died, and just got a res.  You have 0 mana.  You try to cast some sort of buff on yourself.  You wait a tick, stand up, try to cast, not enough mana, sit down again, etc.  For the sake of argument, let's say that it's a spell where you need 30% of a mana bar after you got a rez, and it's a spell that you specialized in.  Finally you hit 30, stand up, cast, the spell takes hold, and hmm, that's odd, you have 3% mana left.  Why didn't it let you cast at 27% then?  The answer is, the 3% mana is the mana you got back from specialization saving you 10% mana (10% of 30% is 3%).  Add a Mana Preservation focus item, and get Spell Casting Mastery, and you'll see over a 30% savings (except for complete healing and percentage heals, they coded mana preservation not to work on those).<br>
<br>
Now, lets think a minute about why SCM and mana savings in general is such a big deal.<br>
<br>
1) It increases your effective mana pool.  Suppose you have a 4030 mana pool, and want to cast a spell that costs 400 mana normally (360 because it's in your spec).  You can cast it 4030/360 =  11.2 times, right?  Now, lets say you go get Spell Casting Mastery 3 and try this experiment again.  Now spells cost you like 310 per cast, you can cast the spell 13 times.  You &quot;effectively&quot; raised your mana pool from 4030 to more like 13x360 = 4680.  That's an <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>effective mana pool gain of over 16%.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
2) It increases your effective mana regeneration.  Suppose (beause you're a shaman with Cann5) that you're regenerating something like 50 mana per tick with everything figured in (not a raid situation, or you'd probably approach 100).  Now, how many ticks does it take you to go from empty to full?  Well your mana pool in #1 above was 4030, so it takes 4030/50 = 80.6 ticks.  But remember, your effective pool  with SCM is 4680, and it takes you 80.6 ticks to get it back, so your effective mana regen turns into 4680 mana / 80.6 ticks = just over 58 mana per tick.  SCM <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>effectively increases your mana regeneration by over 16%.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
3) It not only stacks with other AA abilities and focus items, it stacks multiplicatively.  Take the same shaman with the same mana pool and mana regen who then goes from FT5 to FT15, and adds a 20% mana preservation focus item.  Now a spell in specialization before SCM has a 30% reduction in mana cost, and so if it's 400 base, it's now 310 base.  That's 13 castings without SCM, but with SCM, it's a 42.5% reduction, so the 400 mana spell costs 230 mana.  4030/230 = over 17.5 castings.  Effective mana pool compared to without SCM: 17.52 * 310 = 5432, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>a 35% increase in effective mana pool</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Now let's look at mana regen.  Our shaman is now at 60 mana per tick (increased FT from 5 to 15, so net mana regen goes from 50 to 60).  Now, without SCM, with a mana pool of 4030, it takes 4030/60=67.2 ticks to regen a full bar of mana.  With SCM, it takes the same amount of time to fill up that mana bar, but you're effectively filling up 5432 mana in 67.2 ticks, or over 80 mana per tick.  You see <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>a 35% inrease in effective mana regeneration</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
What I'm trying to say is, get SCM, and it only gets better with age, gear, and AAs.  It's absolutely the best archetype AA out there for casters, and I would go so far as to say the absolute best use of 12 AA points in general.<br>
